# Linux Basics - Day 1

## Print text

echo "Hello, World!"

**Purpose:** Prints text or variables to the terminal.

**Example Output:**

Hello, World!


---

## Display user and group information

id

**Purpose:** Displays your user ID (UID), group ID (GID), and the groups you belong to.

**Example Output:**

uid=1000(username) gid=1000(username) groups=1000(username),27(sudo)


---

## Display only the username

id -un

**Purpose:** Displays only the current user's username.

**Example Output:**

username


---

## Display the current logged-in user

whoami

**Purpose:** Prints the username of the current user.

**Example Output:**

username


**Note:** `whoami` and `id -un` usually produce the same output.

---

## Update package list

sudo apt update

**Purpose:** Updates the package index from configured repositories.

---

## Check available package upgrades


apt list --upgradable


**Purpose:** Lists packages that have newer versions available.

---

## Upgrade installed packages


sudo apt upgrade


**Purpose:** Installs the latest versions of installed packages.

---

## Perform a full upgrade


sudo apt full-upgrade


**Purpose:** Upgrades packages and resolves dependency changes if needed.

---

## Remove unused packages


sudo apt autoremove

**Purpose:** Removes packages that are no longer required.

---

## Reboot the system


sudo reboot


**Purpose:** Restarts the system.

---

## Check disk usage


df -h


**Purpose:** Displays disk space usage in a human-readable format.

---

## Check Git version


git --version


**Purpose:** Displays the installed Git version.

---

## Open the current folder in Visual Studio Code


code .


**Purpose:** Opens the current directory in VS Code.

## apt

`apt` stands for Advanced Package Tool. It is used to manage software packages in Debian-based Linux distributions such as Ubuntu.

## sudo

`sudo` stands for "superuser do". It allows a permitted normal user to execute a specific command with administrator (root) privileges.

`sudo` provides elevated privileges for the command being executed. It does not permanently make the user root.